==English==
===Etymology===
Alkali + -oid: cf. F. alcaloïde.

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /ˈæl.kə.lɔɪd/

===Adjective===
# Pertaining to, resembling, or containing, alkali.
<!-- material copied from Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary (1913) -->

===Noun===
# (Chemistry) An organic base, especially one of a class of substances  occurring ready formed in the tissues of plants and the  bodies of animals.

Note: Alkaloids all contain nitrogen, carbon, and hydrogen, and many of them also contain oxygen. They include many of the active principles in plants; thus, morphine and narcotine are alkaloids found in opium.